 |url         =http://books.google.com/?id=R08VAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA268&vq=leading+europe+abandoning
 |publisher       =A.B. Case.
}}</ref> The last school in the U.S. exclusively teaching homeopathy closed in 1920.<ref name="homhist1"/>

===Revival in the late 20th century===
{{Main|Regulation and prevalence of homeopathy}}
In the United States the ''Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act'' of 1938 (sponsored by [[Royal S. Copeland|Royal Copeland]], a [[United States Senate|Senator]] from [[New York]] and homeopathic physician) recognized homeopathic remedies as drugs. In the 1950s, there were only 75 pure homeopaths practicing in the U.S.<ref>
{{Citation |title       =Homeopathic Hassle
 |url         =http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,891760,00.html
 |work   =[[Time (magazine)|Time]]
 |date        =1956-08-20
}}</ref> However, by the mid to late 1970s, homeopathy made a significant comeback and sales of some homeopathic companies increased tenfold.<ref name=rader>
{{Citation |date        =1985-03-01
 |publisher   =FDA Consumer Magazine
 |author      =Rader WM
 |url         =http://www.homeowatch.org/history/fdac1.html
 |title       =Riding the coattails of homeopathy's revival
}}</ref> Greek homeopath [[George Vithoulkas]] performed a "great deal of research to update the scenarios and refine the theories and practice of homeopathy" beginning in the 1970s, and it was revived worldwide;<ref name="pmid12614092">{{Citation |last1=Harris |first1=L. F. |title=Anaerobic septicemia after transrectal prostatic biopsy |journal=Archives of Internal Medicine |volume=138 |pages=393–9 |year=1978 |doi=10.1001/archinte.138.3.393 |issue=3 |pmid=204264 |last2=Jackson |first2=RT |last3=Breslin Jr |first3=JA |last4=Alford |first4=RH}}</ref><ref>
{{cite book
 |first = Andrew
 |last=Lockie 
 |title       =Encyclopedia of Homeopathy
 |publisher   =[[Dorling Kindersley]]
 |year        =2000
 |location    =New York City, NY
 |edition     =1st
 |page        =19
